Git stash - temporarily saving unsaved changes on your local machine 
Git stash pop = your bring back the changes but it removes them from the stash list now 
Git stash apply = you go back onto the branch and bring back the changes
Git stash list - lists all the temp uncommitted changes 

Git revert <commit> = this undoes that commit - find the commit hash in git log 
Git reset <commit> = moves branch pointer back (soft=keep changes) (mixed unstaged) (hard nuke )
Git cherry-pick <commit> = apply a specific commit to the branch that your on

Fork and pull requests:
When you don’t have access to a remote repo , you can clone it = FORK 

- Git clone the repo 
- Make changes and commit (push) to your FORK ( local repo) 
- Open a pull request so that it can be reviewed and merged into the main branch/project 
- Repo owners review + it’s used a lot in open source 

Without access:
Local rep -> commit changes (push ) -> your FORK -> open pull request -> merged into main branch/repo

With access:
Local repo -> commit changes (push) -> updated local repo -> make pull request -> merged into main branch/repo

Trunk based Development:
All devs commit to main branch / short lived branches 
Have string CI/testing gates = good testing coverage and is automatically tested = good code make it to MAIN DEV branch
Used by fast moving orgs like Google 

